 // The operator-seam report types (`dev/interfaces/rust.md` § 2b) — CLI-only,

codex
The projection substrate can silently omit common scalar JSON values and can retain stale projection rows after logical-id supersession. These are correctness issues in the newly added projection registry/EAV behavior.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Project non-string JSON attribute values — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15d/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:14827-14833
  For projected attributes whose JSON value is numeric or boolean, `json_extract` returns an INTEGER/REAL value rather than TEXT; `row.get::<_, Option<String>>(0)` then fails conversion and `.unwrap_or(None)` silently treats the attribute as absent. This means specs such as a filterable `score` over bodies like `{"score": 3}` never populate `canonical_attributes` or `property_search_index`, so the projection is incomplete for common scalar inputs.

- [P2] Purge superseded attribute projection rows — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15d/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:15153-15154
  When a node with an existing `logical_id` is rewritten after a projection has been declared, the old canonical row is marked superseded but its `canonical_attributes` and `property_search_index` rows are never removed; this new projection path only inserts rows for the replacement cursor. In that scenario, same-session property filters/FTS over the projection can see both the stale and current attribute values until a boot re-derive or reconfigure clears the table, violating the active-only projection invariant.
